  "body": "The constructor of my contract takes in `bytes` type argument.\r\n```solidity\r\nconstructor(bytes _input) {\r\n    â€¦\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\nAnd for example when I pass in \"0xabcdef\" during contract deployment:\r\n```JavaScript\r\nconst factory = await ethers.getContractFactory(\"MyContract\");\r\n\r\n// If we had constructor arguments, they would be passed into deploy()\r\nlet contract = await factory.deploy(\"0xabcdef\");\r\n```\r\nIt would treat the hex string as bytes, not string.\r\n\r\nHowever when I run `npx buidler verify-contract --contract-name MyContract --address DEPLOYED_CONTRACT_ADDRESS 0xabcdef`, the argument `0xabcdef` would be treated as string and parsed as `3078616263646566` and the verification would fail because constructor arguments do not match.",
